I'd like to clean up, so to speak, by making a few small corrections and additions.<br>
<br>
Kansas colleges actually DO have alot of sister-colleges in Japan.  A surprisingly high percent of my Japanese friends have studied English in -guess where- Kansas.  I'm guessing that these exchanges can work both ways.<br>
<br>
You're an engineering/physics student, but you want to go to Japan... errr, if you go as an exchange student from your college, preference is naturally going to be given to language/teaching majors.  <br>
<br>
You've expressed a desire to live in Japan as long as possible...possibly forever.  I'd think that the USA would therefore not particularly want to send you to Japan for security-issues-related stuff... basically, they'd be giving you and your skills to Japan, and not expecting you to &quot;bear fruit&quot; in the US.  If you planned to come back and live and work in the US, I'd think your chances would be better.  Also, consider that taking $ from Feds interested in security issues is not good for peace &amp; peace-of-mind.  It could be a slippery slope into being part of Bush's war-&amp;-paranoia machine.<br>
<br>
MaiMai gives the straight poop on living in Tokyo, the biggest/most expensive city where ALL LIFE BEGINS AND ENDS (just kidding) in Japan. Yes, the apartment prices there would scare the living cr#p outta you.  You'd also be pretty lost, unless your Japanese is really hot, or you score a host family or girlfriend who speak English.<br>
<br>
I'd like to ADD, though, that this is just the picture in TOKYO and its suburbs and the other really big cities.  If you go to slightly smaller cities, or are willing to settle for the countryside, prices go way, way down.  Compare MaiMai's experience with mine:  I live 30 minutes from a city of 1 million people, and I pay a mere $500 a month for a huge, clean 4-room apartment.<br>
<br>
Your grades aren't gonna get anyone excited, I'm afraid.<br>
And, prices here are prohibitively high, if you're not gonna be working...and you don't have a college degree yet.<br>
<br>
If I were in your shoes, I'd therefore try to find an informal homestay situation, by taking out an ad in The Japan Times (costs $) or at GetHiroshima.com .  Assuming that you're a native English speaker and don't have wild habits (noisy, grungy, drunkenness, drug-dealing, sex-maniac, or  motorcycle-gang stuff), you might score by finding someone in Japan who'd be DELIGHTED to have you stay with their family for (for example) your summer vacation.  Think about it from their perspective:  They'd have a live-in English speaker... free English conversation practice !  What a deal.  That's how *I* first came to Japan.<br>
<br>
If you're particularly interested in peace-related issues, you can check out the peace-and-international-relations groups around Hiroshima, who have lots of homestays going on.  Those are generally for highschool kids, though, so do this while you're still relatively young.<br>
<br>
Oh...those peace-groups might also be willing to post an index-card-sized bulletin board message for you, at international centers in Japan. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=higakun>higakun</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://komplx.com/higan/Page_2/IMAG000.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/14/03 8:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1220.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://images.warcry.com/image.php?id=4964 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: As usual, MaiMai speaks the Truth &amp; I clean up after</span><hr size=1> i am going to japan too. but i suggest taking it slow. from what i heard, dont go without money. i will not even get the ticket until i save up 7-10k dollars. i want time to soak up the language and not worry about the rent. i may stay on campus at the university of chiba or apply for a gaijin house. pretty low rent if you are willing to share a room with 4-6 others. a japanese style room mind you. i dont mind. i slept in a closet 4 ft by 10 ft for two years. but thats just me.  i know its expensive to go there if you plan on getting stuff you like. but for me i like sushi, rice, musabi, udon, and the occasional pork bun. then again thats just me. So once again. from someone that has heard of what needs to be done. take it slow. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sethness>SethNess</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/clearhappy.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/15/03 4:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1220.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Bring Lotsa Money</span><hr size=1> Higakun's planning a long stay, with study at a University, I take it.<br>
Yes, it's a good idea, then, to bring major money.  7 to 10k is a reasonable sum, especially if you're not planning to work right away.  The majority of that money will go for initial apartment costs, and possibly an initial phone connection (which can cost up to $700 for the initial installation).<br>
<br>
THe fellow who started the thread might be satisfied with a considerably shorter homestay, I thought, so I suggested an informal homestay.<br>
Since he's without a degree, and without deep pockets, and his college career doesn't seem like a path that leads to Japan, I'm grasping at alternatives that Hikagun needn't consider. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#336699>- </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs>Polykarbon BBS</a><font color=#336699> - </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5>Japanese Language Help</a> <font color=#336699> - </font><a href="http://www.polykarbon.com">Polykarbon: Manga & Photoshop</a><font color=#336699> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.246g<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

